1
00:00:47,630 --> 00:00:48,910
(Faint Cheering)

2
00:00:51,460 --> 00:00:53,510
[Announcer]
Let's welcome our favorite alumnus,

3
00:00:53,510 --> 00:00:56,640
...and the next senator
from the state of New York,

4
00:00:56,640 --> 00:00:57,680
David Norris!

5
00:00:59,810 --> 00:01:01,490
Thank you. Thank you.

6
00:01:02,980 --> 00:01:04,260
Well, hi, there.

7
00:01:05,230 --> 00:01:06,400
My name is David Norris,

8
00:01:06,400 --> 00:01:11,480
...and I'd like to be the next senator 
from the great state of New York.

9
00:01:11,480 --> 00:01:13,150
Look at you. What's your name?

10
00:01:13,150 --> 00:01:14,650
I'm going to go through Yonkers,
door to door...

11
00:01:14,650 --> 00:01:16,820
- ...and take the city that way.
- We love you.

12
00:01:16,820 --> 00:01:18,530
The recent endorsement
by the fire fighter's union...

13
00:01:18,530 --> 00:01:19,990
...is another boost to Norris

14
00:01:19,990 --> 00:01:21,790
...who already had a six-point lead

15
00:01:21,790 --> 00:01:23,330
...over his opponent, Roger Linfield.

16
00:01:23,330 --> 00:01:26,850
Whenever I see you on C-Span,
and you stand,

17
00:01:27,290 --> 00:01:30,380
I always think you're
about to go, "Chug!"

18
00:01:30,380 --> 00:01:32,340
Congressman,
you certainly started your career off,

19
00:01:32,340 --> 00:01:36,820
...eight years ago, with a bang
or should I say, a bust.

20
00:01:42,350 --> 00:01:43,310
(Chattering)

21
00:01:54,190 --> 00:01:56,030
[Bloomberg]
For the last eight years,

22
00:01:56,030 --> 00:02:00,700
David Norris has represented Brooklyn, 
New York City and America.

23
00:02:00,700 --> 00:02:02,990
This is my campaign chairman,
Charlie Traynor.

24
00:02:02,990 --> 00:02:04,080
These are voters.

25
00:02:04,080 --> 00:02:05,950
Latest polls have you up 10 points.

26
00:02:05,950 --> 00:02:07,870
[David]
We're 10 points up?

27
00:02:07,870 --> 00:02:09,750
This is not going to be
easy getting there.

28
00:02:09,750 --> 00:02:11,250
I have some real opposition,

29
00:02:11,250 --> 00:02:12,590
...and what they're saying about me

30
00:02:12,590 --> 00:02:14,710
...is that I'm too young
to hold this office.

31
00:02:14,710 --> 00:02:16,260
Win big, but run like you're 20 down.

32
00:02:16,260 --> 00:02:17,470
Okay, you got it.

33
00:02:17,470 --> 00:02:18,550
Thank you, Gary.

34
00:02:18,550 --> 00:02:20,390
[David] But that's okay because these 
are the same people

35
00:02:20,390 --> 00:02:22,600
...who say that young people don't vote,

36
00:02:22,600 --> 00:02:24,970
...young people don't care about politics,

37
00:02:24,970 --> 00:02:26,560
...but I'm here to tell you,

38
00:02:26,560 --> 00:02:29,560
...your future is about
your choices, not theirs.

39
00:02:29,560 --> 00:02:31,900
So, today I'd like to put them on notice

40
00:02:31,900 --> 00:02:34,820
...because come November,
I want them to know

41
00:02:34,820 --> 00:02:36,820
...that it was young people like you,

42
00:02:36,820 --> 00:02:38,900
...who kicked their asses.

43
00:02:38,950 --> 00:02:40,070
(All Cheering)

44
00:02:42,740 --> 00:02:45,620
[Spectators](Chanting)
David! David!

45
00:02:50,420 --> 00:02:51,220
Thank you.

46
00:02:53,170 --> 00:02:53,810
Charlie.

47
00:02:54,250 --> 00:02:55,290
What's wrong?

48
00:03:06,680 --> 00:03:08,280
(Cell Phone Ringing)

49
00:03:09,430 --> 00:03:10,150
(Sighing)

50
00:03:15,610 --> 00:03:16,010
Yeah?

51
00:03:16,690 --> 00:03:18,530
[Richardson]
Any ideas?

52
00:03:19,490 --> 00:03:20,930
I'm working on it.

53
00:03:20,990 --> 00:03:22,190
Keep me posted.

54
00:03:22,780 --> 00:03:23,180
Yeah.

55
00:03:50,850 --> 00:03:51,980
[Newscaster]
David Norris,

56
00:03:51,980 --> 00:03:54,610
...until recently,
he was way ahead in the polls.

57
00:03:54,610 --> 00:03:57,190
Mary Matalin and James Carville are here.

58
00:03:57,190 --> 00:03:59,190
Mary, this is a surprise.

59
00:03:59,740 --> 00:04:01,820
[Mary]
It is a surprise. Such political promise.

60
00:04:01,820 --> 00:04:04,490
This compelling story, he grew up
in a rough neighborhood in Brooklyn.

61
00:04:04,490 --> 00:04:06,530
He overcame the loss
of his entire family,

62
00:04:06,530 --> 00:04:08,410
...his mom and his brother when he was 10,

63
00:04:08,410 --> 00:04:11,000
...his father before he got to
high school, he got over that.

64
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:12,250
He had such promise.

65
00:04:12,250 --> 00:04:14,650
And he was the youngest person

66
00:04:14,960 --> 00:04:16,960
...ever elected to the
House of Representatives.

67
00:04:16,960 --> 00:04:19,760
[James] Yeah, he was elected
when he was actually 24,

68
00:04:19,760 --> 00:04:22,880
...but he gets in a bar room fight
the night that he's elected.

69
00:04:22,880 --> 00:04:24,340
I like this, all right.

70
00:04:24,340 --> 00:04:26,800
Then you have this photo coming out of 
the New York Post.

71
00:04:26,800 --> 00:04:29,010
I think the accretion of this stuff

72
00:04:29,010 --> 00:04:31,520
...was just too much for the voters.

73
00:04:31,520 --> 00:04:35,850
It reeked of some level
of immaturity here, of impulsiveness.

74
00:04:35,850 --> 00:04:40,490
[Mary] People want maturity,
they want adults in Congress.

75
00:04:51,370 --> 00:04:53,960
[Richardson]
Big night for us, gentlemen.

76
00:04:53,960 --> 00:04:55,240
Everybody ready?

77
00:04:58,920 --> 00:05:00,440
You look exhausted.

78
00:05:00,710 --> 00:05:03,260
You should take a vacation
when all this is finished.

79
00:05:03,260 --> 00:05:04,510
You've earned it.

80
00:05:04,510 --> 00:05:06,180
I'm not sure the kind of tired I am

81
00:05:06,180 --> 00:05:08,390
...can be fixed by a vacation.

82
00:05:08,390 --> 00:05:10,550
Everybody needs a vacation,

83
00:05:10,680 --> 00:05:11,560
...even us.

84
00:05:13,140 --> 00:05:15,390
All right, let's get him back on track.

85
00:05:15,390 --> 00:05:17,020
[Newscaster]
Mary, over the past couple of weeks

86
00:05:17,020 --> 00:05:19,730
...since the photo came out,
they thought people...

87
00:05:19,730 --> 00:05:21,570
Why are you still watching CNN?

88
00:05:21,570 --> 00:05:24,400
[Newscaster] That it wasn't such a big 
deal, but clearly it was.

89
00:05:24,400 --> 00:05:27,600
They called this way too early. Come on.

90
00:05:28,240 --> 00:05:31,120
Put on your pretty
little tie and let's go.

91
00:05:31,120 --> 00:05:32,240
(Phone Ringing)

92
00:05:32,240 --> 00:05:34,080
Suffolk County numbers,

93
00:05:34,410 --> 00:05:36,730
Linfield, 415, 120. Norris...

94
00:05:39,420 --> 00:05:40,060
370,233.

95
00:05:43,260 --> 00:05:43,580
Wow.

96
00:05:46,510 --> 00:05:48,550
I really thought we'd win Suffolk.

97
00:05:48,550 --> 00:05:51,030
Kings County just came in, too.

98
00:05:53,180 --> 00:05:53,740
Well...

99
00:05:55,140 --> 00:05:56,900
I didn't win Brooklyn.

100
00:05:57,810 --> 00:05:59,560
It's going to be a blow out.

101
00:05:59,560 --> 00:06:01,080
NBC has us up next.

102
00:06:05,610 --> 00:06:06,900
I'm going to go work on my speech.

103
00:06:06,900 --> 00:06:07,540
David...

104
00:06:08,110 --> 00:06:08,990
David. Hey!

105
00:06:11,700 --> 00:06:14,740
I'm sorry I wasted your time, Charlie.

106
00:06:18,120 --> 00:06:22,130
NBC news is now calling the election 
for Roger Linfield.

107
00:06:22,130 --> 00:06:24,670
After a shockingly
poor showing at both Suffolk County,

108
00:06:24,670 --> 00:06:26,470
...and his home county, Kings,

109
00:06:26,470 --> 00:06:31,350
...it now appears David Norris
will lose this election badly.

110
00:06:39,100 --> 00:06:39,580
Hello?

111
00:06:41,650 --> 00:06:42,130
Hello?

112
00:06:43,150 --> 00:06:44,230
(Softly)
I grew up in Red Hook,

113
00:06:44,230 --> 00:06:45,650
and I don't want to surprise anybody,

114
00:06:45,650 --> 00:06:47,740
...but I got into a few
fistfights along the way.

115
00:06:47,740 --> 00:06:49,030
It's not whether or not you get knocked 
down,

116
00:06:49,030 --> 00:06:50,660
...it's what you do when you get back up.

117
00:06:50,660 --> 00:06:52,490
Ladies and gentlemen,
I'm here tonight to tell you

118
00:06:52,490 --> 00:06:54,010
I will get back up.

119
00:06:54,790 --> 00:06:55,510
(Sighing)

120
00:06:56,500 --> 00:06:57,750
But tonight is not about me.

121
00:06:57,750 --> 00:06:59,040
It is about coming together

122
00:06:59,040 --> 00:07:01,420
...and welcoming the newest senator

123
00:07:01,420 --> 00:07:04,220
...for the great state of New York,

124
00:07:06,090 --> 00:07:07,290
Roger Linfield.

125
00:07:08,090 --> 00:07:09,170
(Metal Clinks)

126
00:07:09,170 --> 00:07:10,210
[Elise]
Shit!

127
00:07:11,010 --> 00:07:12,370
Shit, shit, shit.

128
00:07:13,640 --> 00:07:14,120
Hello?

129
00:07:26,690 --> 00:07:28,610
- It's the men's.
- Yep.

130
00:07:31,910 --> 00:07:34,200
Sorry about that.
I didn't mean to eavesdrop.

131
00:07:34,200 --> 00:07:36,600
I just didn't know what to do.

132
00:07:37,040 --> 00:07:38,500
I heard you come in and say, "Hello,"

133
00:07:38,500 --> 00:07:40,210
...and I probably should have said, "Hi,"

134
00:07:40,210 --> 00:07:42,040
...but then I thought that would be weird

135
00:07:42,040 --> 00:07:43,920
...because it's the men's.

136
00:07:43,920 --> 00:07:46,800
Then you started talking to yourself

137
00:07:47,210 --> 00:07:48,840
...and it was obviously very personal.

138
00:07:48,840 --> 00:07:51,130
So I was stuck in no man's land,

139
00:07:51,130 --> 00:07:53,800
...and then it all got to be too much,
so I came out.

140
00:07:53,800 --> 00:07:55,960
What are you doing in here?

141
00:07:56,390 --> 00:07:57,030
(Laughs)

142
00:07:57,640 --> 00:07:58,200
Just...

143
00:07:59,560 --> 00:08:01,560
I'm hiding from security.

144
00:08:02,230 --> 00:08:03,270
(Laughs)
Why?

145
00:08:03,600 --> 00:08:05,920
I crashed a wedding upstairs.

146
00:08:06,110 --> 00:08:07,790
People still do that?

147
00:08:08,980 --> 00:08:10,100
It was a dare.

148
00:08:11,030 --> 00:08:13,670
Who dared you to crash a wedding?

149
00:08:15,660 --> 00:08:15,900
Me.

150
00:08:16,910 --> 00:08:17,150
Oh.

151
00:08:20,290 --> 00:08:22,290
- I crashed a wedding once.
- Did you?

152
00:08:22,290 --> 00:08:23,750
Yeah, in high school.

153
00:08:23,750 --> 00:08:23,990
Oh.

154
00:08:25,580 --> 00:08:28,550
But I got caught.
I spent the night in jail.

155
00:08:28,550 --> 00:08:31,760
I think that happened more than once 
from what I heard.

156
00:08:31,760 --> 00:08:34,220
You're that guy
running for Senate, aren't you?

157
00:08:34,220 --> 00:08:35,820
Yeah, I am that guy.

158
00:08:36,090 --> 00:08:38,560
And judging from your speech,
you're not winning?

159
00:08:38,560 --> 00:08:38,800
No.

160
00:08:40,100 --> 00:08:43,060
Oh. That's too bad,
the other guy is such a tool.

161
00:08:43,060 --> 00:08:44,730
(Laughing)
He is a tool.

162
00:08:44,730 --> 00:08:47,690
I wish I could have made that clearer 
in the campaign ads.

163
00:08:47,690 --> 00:08:49,570
Personally, I think mooning your friends

164
00:08:49,570 --> 00:08:52,150
...at a college reunion is no big deal.

165
00:08:52,150 --> 00:08:54,280
The Post did not have to run the photo.

166
00:08:54,280 --> 00:08:56,450
(Exhales)
At least not a full page.

167
00:08:56,450 --> 00:08:57,090
God, no.

168
00:08:57,700 --> 00:08:58,900
(Both Laughing)

169
00:09:00,120 --> 00:09:02,870
It was my favorite moment
of your whole campaign.

170
00:09:02,870 --> 00:09:04,830
Really? I could have used you on my team

171
00:09:04,830 --> 00:09:06,290
...a couple of months ago.

172
00:09:06,290 --> 00:09:07,460
I could help poll test

173
00:09:07,460 --> 00:09:10,250
...every word that comes
out of your mouth before you say it.

174
00:09:10,250 --> 00:09:11,630
Oh, you like politicians?

175
00:09:11,630 --> 00:09:13,840
I like it when they do
stuff I can relate to.

176
00:09:13,840 --> 00:09:17,260
- Like pull their pants down?
- I love that.

177
00:09:17,260 --> 00:09:20,510
See, that kind of candidate wouldn't 
even get elected to the student council.

178
00:09:20,510 --> 00:09:22,560
My guy would know
how to tie his own tie.

179
00:09:22,560 --> 00:09:23,680
It's a clip-on.

180
00:09:23,680 --> 00:09:24,560
Oh, I wish.

181
00:09:25,480 --> 00:09:30,520
That would have been my other
favorite moment of your campaign.

182
00:09:30,650 --> 00:09:32,190
Do you still have a chance?

183
00:09:32,190 --> 00:09:33,070
Is it over?

184
00:09:34,070 --> 00:09:35,190
He crushed me.

185
00:09:36,780 --> 00:09:38,060
(Exhales)
Sorry.

186
00:09:38,370 --> 00:09:40,490
Well, losing has its advantages.

187
00:09:40,490 --> 00:09:41,290
Like what?

188
00:09:42,120 --> 00:09:45,210
For one thing, as a politician,
you're never really alone

189
00:09:45,210 --> 00:09:48,880
...unless you're asleep,
or in the bathroom usually.

190
00:09:48,880 --> 00:09:50,000
That gets old.

191
00:09:51,340 --> 00:09:51,900
Really?

192
00:09:53,000 --> 00:09:55,590
Yeah, I guess I'm mostly just looking 
forward

193
00:09:55,590 --> 00:09:58,230
...to having some time by myself.

194
00:10:01,180 --> 00:10:04,060
I don't buy it. I think you love it.

195
00:10:07,690 --> 00:10:08,810
Do I know you?

196
00:10:09,440 --> 00:10:10,400
(Both Laugh)

197
00:10:16,360 --> 00:10:18,320
I guess I could have been more convincing.

198
00:10:18,320 --> 00:10:18,720
Okay.

199
00:10:19,450 --> 00:10:22,950
You don't have to worry about being 
convincing till the next election.

200
00:10:22,950 --> 00:10:25,040
Are you a registered New York voter?

201
00:10:25,040 --> 00:10:26,720
Do I sound like I am?

202
00:10:43,390 --> 00:10:44,190
Holy shit.

203
00:10:47,770 --> 00:10:49,050
[Charlie]
David.

204
00:10:49,810 --> 00:10:51,490
Oh. Wow, sorry, guys.

205
00:10:53,060 --> 00:10:54,900
- Sorry.
- I got to go.

206
00:10:56,780 --> 00:10:57,260
Sorry.

207
00:11:00,240 --> 00:11:01,360
- Wow.
- Hang on.

208
00:11:01,360 --> 00:11:03,200
- You going to give your speech?
- Hang on.

209
00:11:03,200 --> 00:11:03,520
Hey!

210
00:11:04,990 --> 00:11:05,310
Hey.

211
00:11:08,250 --> 00:11:08,730
Ma'am.

212
00:11:09,410 --> 00:11:10,370
I got to go.

213
00:11:11,670 --> 00:11:12,150
Ma'am?

214
00:11:12,750 --> 00:11:14,170
That is so much better.

215
00:11:14,170 --> 00:11:15,610
She's on the move.

216
00:11:16,760 --> 00:11:18,300
Southwest staircase.

217
00:11:18,300 --> 00:11:19,660
Excuse me? Ma'am.

218
00:11:20,970 --> 00:11:22,090
What was that?

219
00:11:23,090 --> 00:11:24,130
I don't know.

220
00:11:25,100 --> 00:11:26,220
Are you ready?

221
00:11:26,850 --> 00:11:27,730
Yeah, yeah.

222
00:11:28,770 --> 00:11:31,270
All right, go do the speech. Come on.

223
00:11:31,270 --> 00:11:34,230
[Announcer]
Congressman David Norris.

224
00:11:34,270 --> 00:11:35,390
(All Cheering)

225
00:11:37,820 --> 00:11:40,110
I grew up not far away from here, in 
Red Hook.

226
00:11:40,110 --> 00:11:42,280
- [Man] Brooklyn!
- [Woman] I love you, David!

227
00:11:42,280 --> 00:11:43,990
[Woman #2]
I love you more!

228
00:11:43,990 --> 00:11:45,270
I love you both.

229
00:11:45,490 --> 00:11:46,610
(All Laughing)

230
00:11:46,700 --> 00:11:49,500
But we had a rule in my neighborhood.

231
00:11:49,500 --> 00:11:51,420
When you got in a fight,

232
00:11:53,080 --> 00:11:56,290
...it wasn't whether or not
you got knocked down,

233
00:11:56,290 --> 00:11:59,570
...it's what you do when you get back up.

234
00:12:00,260 --> 00:12:01,060
(Cheering)

235
00:12:04,010 --> 00:12:05,930
And I came here to tell you tonight,

236
00:12:05,930 --> 00:12:07,850
...that I will get back up.

237
00:12:08,810 --> 00:12:09,610
(Cheering)

238
00:12:25,490 --> 00:12:26,610
It's bullshit.

239
00:12:27,530 --> 00:12:30,870
We didn't have that saying in my 
neighborhood.

240
00:12:30,870 --> 00:12:33,270
It's just one of those phrases

241
00:12:34,870 --> 00:12:37,170
...that had some traction
with the focus group

242
00:12:37,170 --> 00:12:40,210
...and so we kept using it,
but it's not true.

243
00:12:40,210 --> 00:12:43,090
In 1998, I did a cover story for GQ.

244
00:12:43,170 --> 00:12:46,340
The title was "Youngest Congressman 
Ever."

245
00:12:46,340 --> 00:12:48,260
And since then, every story has tried

246
00:12:48,260 --> 00:12:51,220
...to explain how I got here so fast.

247
00:12:52,850 --> 00:12:57,010
And the word that
people kept using was "authentic."

248
00:12:58,190 --> 00:12:59,310
(All Cheering)

249
00:12:59,940 --> 00:13:01,780
But here's the problem.

250
00:13:05,160 --> 00:13:07,000
This isn't even my tie.

251
00:13:08,240 --> 00:13:10,370
- Go get Jim for me.
- This tie was selected for me

252
00:13:10,370 --> 00:13:14,450
...by a group of specialists
in Tenafly, New Jersey

253
00:13:14,540 --> 00:13:18,220
...who chose it over
56 other ties we tested. 

254
00:13:18,710 --> 00:13:22,790
In fact, our data suggests that I have 
to stick to

255
00:13:23,090 --> 00:13:26,930
...either a tie that is red
or a tie that is blue.

256
00:13:26,930 --> 00:13:30,640
A yellow tie made it look as if I was 
taking my situation lightly,

257
00:13:30,640 --> 00:13:33,270
...and I may in fact,
pull my pants down again at any moment.

258
00:13:33,270 --> 00:13:34,390
(All Laughing)

259
00:13:35,020 --> 00:13:38,860
A silver tie meant that I'd forgotten 
my roots.

260
00:13:39,560 --> 00:13:40,440
My shoes...

261
00:13:41,570 --> 00:13:43,330
You know, shiny shoes,

262
00:13:43,570 --> 00:13:47,810
...we associate
with high-priced lawyers and bankers.

263
00:13:48,990 --> 00:13:50,530
If you want to get a working man's vote,

264
